<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-437-998  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 437 998.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>MacWEEK  May 15 1990 v4 n19 p10(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Coastal Associates Publishing L.P. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Xerox suit against Apple peters out. (Xerox Corp. lawsuit againstApple Computer Inc.)andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Said, Carolyn.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Apple Computer Inc. (cases)Xerox Corp. (cases).andO;Ticker:    XRX; AAPL.andO;Topic:     Law SuitLegal IssuesCopyrightComputer Industry.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By Carolyn SaidandM;San Francisco -- Xerox Corp.'s lawsuit against Apple, which made a big bangwhen it was filed in December, has ended -- at least for the time being -- ona quiet note.andM;At a hearing before U.S.andP;  District Judge Vaughn Walker here last week,attorneys for Xerox agreed to have the remaining count in the case dismissed.andM;Walker had already thrown out five of six counts in Xerox's $150 million suitthat claimed that the Lisa and Macintosh Finder copy parts of Xerox's 1981Star computer system (see MacWEEK, April 3).andM;Xerox attorneys said they could not meet the standards Walker had set forthem to prove the remaining count, in which Xerox claimed it feared Applemight sue Xerox or its customers.andM;&quot;It looks like Xerox is fishing around for a face-saving way to back out ofthe whole thing,&quot; said Jerry Cohen, a Boston-based attorney specializing incomputer law.andP;  &quot;If they had enough of a case [to file in the first place], itshould have been enough to go into court even with a greater burden ofproof.&quot;andM;Xerox will have 30 days to decide if it wants to file an appeal.andP;  A companyrepresentative would not comment on Xerox's plans; after Walker's Marchdecision, however, the company had said it would appeal.andM;Should Xerox appeal, the case most likely would be scuttled again by thefeeble legal arguments necessitated by its lateness, experts said.andM;&quot;Unfortunately, Xerox waited too long to bring its case,&quot; said G. GervaiseDavis, a Monterey, Calif.-based attorney.andP;  &quot;Even though it would have had anexcellent case seven years ago, it couldn't get around the statute oflimitations.andP;  I don't think Xerox can get anywhere on appeal.&quot; n</TEXT></DOC>